Q: In the coordinate plane, a triangle has vertices at (a,0), (b,0), and (x,y). If a>x>b>0>y, which of the following represents the area of that triangle?
Options: (a) (ay−by)/2 (b) (ab−ay)/2 (c) (by−ay)/2 (d) (ay+by)/x (e) (a−b)/2y
A:
The area of the triangle = (1/2)(base × height). Since the triangle is right-angled, the height is perpendicular to the base. So, the area of the triangle = (1/2)(base × height) = (1/2)(x × y) = (x × y)/2. So the answer is (a).

